# Development Workflow

Before making changes:

- Read and understand the existing implementation in context.
- Search for related screens, hooks, components, and utils before editing.
- Prefer minimal, targeted modifications over large refactors.
- Do not rewrite working systems unnecessarily.

# Implementation Discovery

Before creating new components, hooks, screens, or utilities:

- Search `app/`, `src/components/`, `src/hooks/`, and `src/utils/` for existing implementations.
- Reuse or extend existing code where possible.
- Avoid duplicate modules that overlap in purpose.

# Coding Style

- Keep solutions simple and proportional to the task.
- Avoid overengineering and unnecessary abstractions.
- Avoid adding dependencies unless clearly justified.
- Match surrounding naming, patterns, and documentation level.

# Git

## When commits are allowed

Create a commit after a completed implementation task when **all** of the following are true:

- Available quality checks pass (see Pre-commit checks below)
- No secrets or environment files are staged
- The implementation is complete — not a half-finished feature
- No accidental unrelated files are included in the commit
- The user has not explicitly said not to commit

Do **not** create commits when:

- `npm run lint` fails (when lint script exists)
- Relevant tests fail (when test script exists)
- TypeScript check fails (when configured)
- The implementation is incomplete
- The user explicitly says not to commit
- Sensitive files are modified or staged

Before committing, review `git status` and `git diff` — stage only files related to the completed task.

## Pre-commit checks (run what exists)

```bash
npm run lint          # if defined in package.json
npm run typecheck     # if defined
npm test              # if defined
npx tsc --noEmit      # if TypeScript configured and no typecheck script
npx expo-doctor       # Expo projects
```

## Commit message format

```
<type>(<scope>): <short summary>
```

Examples:

- `feat(game): add local card deck fallback`
- `fix(lobby): handle missing player on reconnect`
- `docs(project): update AI framework status`
- `chore(cursor): add reusable Cursor AI project framework`

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `chore`, `test`, `refactor`.

# Versioning

App version lives in `app.json` (`expo.version`) and `package.json` (`version`).

- Do not bump version during ordinary feature work.
- Bump before store/EAS release builds or when the user explicitly requests it.
- For EAS builds, also update `expo.android.versionCode` / `expo.ios.buildNumber` when configured.

Follow `.cursor/rules/release-workflow.mdc` for release gates.

# Documentation

When functionality, architecture, or status changes:

- Update `project.md` implementation status and known issues.
- Update relevant docs under `docs/`.
- Keep task completion and blocker tables accurate — do not mark unverified work as done.
